subSection.paragraph:
Allorhogas Gahan (1912)
is a doryctine ( Braconidae ) wasp with 64 currently recognised species (
Joele et al . 2019
, 2021 ;
Samacá-Sáenz et al . 2020
;
Yu et al . 2016
;
Zaldívar-Riverón et al . 2014
, 2018 ). The majority of these species occur in the Neotropics (56 species), six in the Nearctic, and two in Asia in northern India and the Middle East, although the species assignment for the latter two need to be confirmed ( Fischer 1960 ; Shaikh & Chatterjee 2020 ). Of the species of
Allorhogas
where their biology has been reported are associated with plant galls or seeds, and they have been confirmed or presumed to be phytophagous of twelve plant families (
Joele et al. 2021
;
Moreira et al . 2017
;
Zaldívar-Riverón et al . 2018
).

The biological information that has been recorded for members of
Allorhogas
indicate the occurrence of several strategies of phytophagy within the genus. Some species have been reared from galls induced by other insects, being phytophagous inquilines (
Moreira et al . 2017
). Other species induce galls on tissues and organs of different plant families such as Fabaceae , Melastomataceae , and Solanaceae , including seeds, stems, fruits and floral buds ( Centrella and Shaw 2010 ;
Chavarría et al . 2009
; Macêdo and Monteiro 1989 ;
Joele et al. 2019
;
Martínez et al. 2011
a;
Zaldívar-Riverón et al . 2018
). In addition, some species are seed predators with or without making galls ( Macêdo & Monteiro 1989 ; Morales-Silva & Modesto-Zampieron 2017 ;
Tuller et al . 2015
;
Zaldívar-Riverón et al . 2018
). Although some species have been suggested to be parasitoids of other insects associated with galls ( Centrella & Shaw 2013 ; Marsh 2002 ), this has not been confirmed by reliable rearing data.

Fruits from long stems of the above two plant species were collected with the aid of pruning shears and subsequently stored in paper bags properly identified in the field, and later moved to the Laboratory of Ecology and Complexity of the University Federal de Lavras. All fruits were collected while still attached to the plant and were closed. We stored each fruit in labelled PVC tubes covered with voile tissue to enable air circulation. This technique allows the development of organisms contained in fruits after their emergence (
Tuller et al. 2015
). The type specimens of the two described species are deposited in the Colección Nacional de Insectos ( CNIN ), Instituto de Biología, Universidad Nacional Autónoma de México ( IBUNAM ).

We molecularly characterized the two newly described species generating DNA sequences belonging to the barcoding locus (Hebert et al. 2003; GenBank accession nos PP162906-07). We extracted genomic DNA of one specimen of each species using the EZ-10 spin column animal genomic DNA miniprep kit (Bio Basic) following the manufacturer’s protocol. We amplified a 629 bp of the cytochrome oxidase I (COI) mitochondrial DNA gene using the primers HCO 1490 and LCO 2198 (
Folmer et al . 1996
) and the Apex Taq RED Master Mix 2X (Apex Bioresearch Products). Reactions consisted of 00:45 s at 94º C for initial denaturation, followed by 35 cycles of 00:15 s annealing 52 º C, and 00:30 s at 75° C for the extension.Amplicons were Sanger sequenced at the University of Arizona Genetics Core.

